    "body": "Custom app folders (or asar files as-of a recent build at least) just don't\nwork at-all - but people keep saying things like\n\nelectron myapp\n\nWhich kinda suggests it does work - which is why I asked the question\nreally.\n\nAt some point I suspect people may want to shop an Electron application\nwhich contains more than 1 app - so the ability to pass the app name\n(searched for as an asar or directory) would be nice (and it's implied that\nit works but right now doesn't?)\n\nor\n\nIf that's not possible, we need to stop suggesting it is in examples - if\nit searches a set of presets (app.asar, resources\\apps\\app,\nresources\\apps\\default_app) then that could be made clearer at least?\n\nOn 13 August 2015 at 15:49, Frank Hale notifications@github.com wrote:\n\n> If your app is in the resources folder either as an app.asar, contained in\n> a folder called app or default_app you won't need to tell Electron where it\n> is. The folder resources\\app or resources\\default_app must be the root of\n> your application.\n> \n> Having your app in the app folder like this is most likely not going to\n> work:\n> \n> resources\\app\\my_app\n> \n> The way I choose to run Electron is to just put my app in resources\\app\n> and double click Electron.exe.\n> \n> â€”\n> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub\n> https://github.com/atom/electron/issues/2492#issuecomment-130715813.\n"
